<h2 id="preface">Preface</h2>

<p>è®¸å¤šå­¦ç”Ÿç¬¬ä¸€æ¬¡è¢«è¦æ±‚åšè¯æ˜æ—¶ä¼šæ„Ÿåˆ°ä¸çŸ¥æ‰€æªï¼Œå› ä¸ºä»–ä»¬åœ¨é«˜ä¸­æ—¶æ‰€å­¦çš„è¯æ˜å¾ˆå¯èƒ½åªæœ‰å‡ ä½•å­¦è¯¾å ‚ä¸Šé‚£ç§ç®€å•çº¿æ€§çš„æ€ç»´ã€‚å°±åƒæ—©æœŸçš„ç¼–ç¨‹ï¼Œäººä»¬åªæ˜¯å°†å‘½ä»¤ä¸€è¡Œè¡Œåœ°å¾€ä¸‹åˆ—ï¼Œç›´åˆ°åæ¥â€œç»“æ„åŒ–ç¼–ç¨‹â€çš„å‡ºç°ã€‚ä¹Ÿå°±æ˜¯è¯´ï¼Œå‘½ä»¤å…·æœ‰äº†å¤æ‚çš„åµŒå¥—ç»“æ„ï¼Œæ¯”å¦‚åœ¨ while å¾ªç¯ä¸­å¯ä»¥æœ‰ if else æ¡ä»¶åˆ¤æ–­ï¼Œç”šè‡³å¦ä¸€ä¸ªå¾ªç¯ã€‚åšè¯æ˜ä¹Ÿæ˜¯ä¸€æ ·çš„ã€‚ä¸€ä¸ªè¯æ˜é€šå¸¸ä¼šç»“åˆå¤šä¸ªåŸºæœ¬ç»“æ„ã€‚è¿™ä¹Ÿæ˜¯æœ¬ä¹¦ä¹¦åçš„ç”±æ¥ã€‚</p>

<p>å› ä¸ºä¸€ä¸ªè¯æ˜çš„ç»“æ„å–å†³äºå‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘å½¢å¼ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥æœ¬ä¹¦ç¬¬ä¸€ç« å’Œç¬¬äºŒç« åˆ†åˆ«ä»‹ç»äº†é€»è¾‘è¿è¯å’Œé‡è¯ï¼Œä»¥åŠé›†åˆè®ºï¼Œä»¥ä¾¿äºè§£é‡Šé€»è¾‘å…³ç³»ã€‚ç¬¬ä¸‰ç« ç³»ç»Ÿåœ°é˜è¿°äº†ç»“æ„åŒ–è¯æ˜çš„æŠ€å·§ã€‚ç¬¬å››ç« å’Œç¬¬äº”ç« å…³äºå…³ç³»å’Œå‡½æ•°ï¼Œè¿™æ˜¯æ•°å­¦æ‰€æœ‰åˆ†æ”¯éƒ½ä¼šæ¶‰åŠåˆ°çš„åŸºç¡€æ¦‚å¿µã€‚ç¬¬å…­ç« å…³äºæ•°å­¦æ¨å¯¼ï¼Œè¿™ä¸ªæ— è®ºåœ¨æ•°å­¦è¿˜æ˜¯è®¡ç®—æœºç§‘å­¦ä¸Šéƒ½ååˆ†é‡è¦çš„è¯æ˜æ–¹æ³•ã€‚æœ€ååœ¨ç¬¬ä¸ƒç« ï¼Œå‰æ–‡æ‰€è¿°çš„æ‰€æœ‰æ–¹æ³•éƒ½ä¼šè¢«æ•´åˆåœ¨ä¸€èµ·ï¼Œæ¥å®Œæˆä¸€äº›æœ€éš¾å´æœ€æœ‰æ„æ€çš„è¯æ˜ã€‚</p>

<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>æ•°å­¦çš„æ ¸å¿ƒæ–¹æ³•æ˜¯ <mark>æ¼”ç»æ¨ç†ï¼ˆdeductive reasoningï¼‰</mark> ï¼šä½ éœ€è¦é€šè¿‡ç°æœ‰çš„ä¿¡æ¯ï¼Œæ¨ç†å‡ºæƒ³çŸ¥é“çš„ä¿¡æ¯ã€‚è€Œæ¼”ç»æ¨ç†åœ¨æ•°å­¦ä¸­é€šå¸¸ä»¥ <mark>è¯æ˜ï¼ˆproofï¼‰</mark> çš„å½¢å¼å‘ˆç°ã€‚æ¥ä¸‹æ¥ä¸¾å‡ ä¸ªä¾‹å­ï¼Œè®©ä½ æ„Ÿå—ä¸‹è¯æ˜æ˜¯ä»€ä¹ˆã€‚çœ‹ä¸å¤ªæ‡‚æ²¡å…³ç³»ï¼Œç­‰ä½ çœ‹å®Œç¬¬ä¸‰ç« å°±ä¼šæ˜ç™½äº†ã€‚</p>

<p>è®©æˆ‘ä»¬æ¥åšä¸€äº›å…³äºè´¨æ•°çš„è¯æ˜å§ï¼å›å¿†ï¼šè´¨æ•°æ˜¯å¤§äº 1 çš„ã€ä¸èƒ½è¢«æ¯”å®ƒå°çš„æ­£æ•´æ•°æ•´é™¤çš„æ•´æ•°ã€‚ä½†æ˜¯åœ¨åŠ¨æ‰‹è¯æ˜ä¹‹å‰ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬è¦å…ˆçŸ¥é“è¯¥è¯æ˜ä»€ä¹ˆå•Šï¼ˆå°±åƒè¯»ç ”ï¼‰ã€‚å› ä¸ºè®¸å¤šçµæ„Ÿéƒ½æ¥è‡ªäºè§‚å¯Ÿï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥æˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥å…ˆåˆ—å‡ºä¸€äº›ä¾‹å­ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{ r l r l }
n &amp; \text{ Is } n \text{ prime? } &amp; 2^n - 1 &amp; \text{Is } 2^n - 1 \text{ prime? } \\
\hline
2 &amp; \text{yes} &amp; 3 &amp; \text{yes} \\
3 &amp; \text{yes} &amp; 7 &amp; \text{yes} \\
4 &amp; \text{no: } 4 = 2 \cdot 2 &amp; 15 &amp; \text{no: } 15 = 3 \cdot 5 \\
5 &amp; \text{yes} &amp; 31 &amp; \text{yes} \\
6 &amp; \text{no: } 6 = 2 \cdot 3 &amp; 63 &amp; \text{no: } 63 = 7 \cdot 9 \\
7 &amp; \text{yes} &amp; 127 &amp; \text{yes} \\
8 &amp; \text{no: } 8 = 2 \cdot 4 &amp; 255 &amp; \text{no: } 255 = 15 \cdot 17 \\
9 &amp; \text{no: } 9 = 3 \cdot 3 &amp; 511 &amp; \text{no: } 511 = 7 \cdot 73 \\
10 &amp; \text{no: } 10 = 2 \cdot 5 &amp; 1023 &amp; \text{no: } 1023 = 31 \cdot 33 \\
\end{array}\]

<p>é€šè¿‡è§‚å¯Ÿä¸Šè¡¨ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥æå‡ºè®¸å¤š <mark>çŒœæƒ³ï¼ˆconjectureï¼‰</mark>ï¼Œæ¯”å¦‚ ï¼š</p>

<p><strong>çŒœæƒ³ 1</strong> Suppose \(n\) is an integer larger than 1 and \(n\) is prime. Then \(2^n - 1\) is prime.</p>

<p><strong>çŒœæƒ³ 2</strong> Suppose \(n\) is an integer larger than 1 and \(n\) is not prime. Then \(2^n - 1\) is not prime.</p>

<p>å¯¹äºçŒœæƒ³ 1ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬åªéœ€è¦ç»§ç»­å¡«å†™åˆ—è¡¨å°±ä¼šå‘ç°ï¼šå½“ n ä¸º 11 æ—¶ï¼ŒçŒœæƒ³é”™è¯¯ã€‚å› æ­¤ï¼Œ11 æ˜¯çŒœæƒ³ 1 çš„ä¸€ä¸ª <mark>åä¾‹ï¼ˆcounterexampleï¼‰</mark>ã€‚ç¡®å®šâ€œä¸€ä¸ªçŒœæƒ³æ˜¯é”™è¯¯çš„â€å¾ˆå®¹æ˜“ï¼Œåªéœ€ä¸€ä¸ªåä¾‹ã€‚ä½†è¦ç¡®å®šâ€œä¸€ä¸ªçŒœæƒ³æ˜¯æ­£ç¡®çš„â€ï¼Œåªèƒ½é€šè¿‡ <mark>è¯æ˜ï¼ˆproveï¼‰</mark>ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>çŒœæƒ³ 2 çš„è¯æ˜</strong> æ—¢ç„¶ \(n\) ä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆå­˜åœ¨æ­£æ•´æ•° \(a\) å’Œ \(b\)ï¼Œä½¿å¾— \(a &lt; nï¼Œb &lt; n\)ï¼Œä¸” \(n = ab\)ã€‚ä»¤ \(x = 2^b-1\) ä¸” \(y = 1 + 2^b + 2^{2b} + \cdots + 2^{(a-1)b}\)ï¼Œåˆ™</p>

\[\begin{align*}
xy &amp; = (2^b-1) \cdot (1 + 2^b + 2^{2b} + \cdots + 2^{(a-1)b}) \\
&amp; = 2^b \cdot (1 + 2^b + 2^{2b} + \cdots + 2^{(a-1)b} ) - (1 + 2^b + 2^{2b} + \cdots + 2^{(a-1)b}) \\
&amp; = (2^b + 2^{2b} + 2^{3b} + \cdots + 2^{ab}) - (1 + 2^b + 2^{2b} + \cdots + 2^{(a-1)b}) \\
&amp; = 2^{ab} - 1 \\
&amp; = 2^n - 1 \\
\end{align*}\]

<p>ç”±æ­¤å¯è§ï¼Œ\(2^n - 1\) æ€»æ˜¯å¯è¢«å†™ä¸ºä¸¤ä¸ªæ›´å°çš„æ­£æ•´æ•° \(x\) å’Œ \(y\) ä¹‹ä¹˜ç§¯ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥ \(2^n - 1\) ä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ï¼ŒçŒœæƒ³ 2 ä¸ºçœŸã€‚</p>

<p><strong>è¯æ¯•</strong></p>

<p>ä¸Šé¢çš„è¯æ˜çš„æ€è·¯æ˜¯å¯»æ‰¾ä¸€ä¸ªè”ç³»äº†å‰æå’Œç»“è®ºçš„æ•°çš„å½¢å¼ï¼Œç›´æ¥å¥—ç”¨å®šä¹‰ã€‚</p>

<p>è¢«è¯æ˜ä¸ºçœŸçš„çŒœæƒ³å°±å¯ä»¥æˆä¸º <mark>å®šç†ï¼ˆtheoremï¼‰</mark> äº†ï¼Œå³ï¼š</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 1</strong> å¦‚æœ \(n\) æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªå¤§äº 1 çš„æ•´æ•°ä¸” \(n\) æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆ \(2^n - 1\) æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 2</strong> å¦‚æœ \(n\) æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªå¤§äº 1 çš„æ•´æ•°ä¸” \(n\) ä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆ \(2^n - 1\) ä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ã€‚</p>

<p>ä¸‹é¢å†çœ‹ä¸€ä¸ªè‘—åçš„è¯æ˜ï¼Œå®ƒæ˜¯ç”±æ¬§å‡ é‡Œå¾·ç»™å‡ºçš„ï¼š</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 3</strong> è´¨æ•°çš„ä¸ªæ•°æ˜¯æ— ç©·çš„ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>è¯æ˜</strong> å‡è®¾è´¨æ•°çš„ä¸ªæ•°æ˜¯æœ‰é™çš„ï¼Œå¹¶å°†æ‰€æœ‰çš„è´¨æ•°è®°ä¸º \(p_1, p_2, \cdots , p_n\)ã€‚å¯¹äºæ•° \(m = p_1p_2 \cdots p_n + 1\)ï¼Œç”±äºå®ƒå¤§äº 1ï¼Œä¸”ä¸èƒ½è¢«ä»»ä½•ä¸€ä¸ªè´¨æ•° \(p_i\) æ•´é™¤ï¼ˆä½™æ•°æ€»æ˜¯ä¸º 1 ï¼‰ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥å®ƒåº”è¯¥æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªè´¨æ•°ã€‚ä½†å®ƒå´ä¸åœ¨æˆ‘ä»¬çš„æœ‰é™è´¨æ•°åˆ—è¡¨é‡Œï¼Œäº§ç”ŸçŸ›ç›¾ã€‚æ‰€ä»¥å‡è®¾ä¸æˆç«‹ï¼Œå®šç† 3 å¾—è¯ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>è¯æ¯•</strong></p>

<p>ä¸Šé¢çš„è¯æ˜çš„æ€è·¯æ˜¯å½’è°¬æ³•ã€‚</p>

<p>å†æ¥ä¸ªé•¿çš„ï¼Œå¥—è·¯ä»ç„¶æ˜¯æ‰¾å½¢å¼å¥—å®šä¹‰ï¼š</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 4</strong> å¯¹äºæ¯ä¸ªæ­£æ•´æ•° \(n\)ï¼Œæ€»å­˜åœ¨è¿ç»­çš„ \(n\) ä¸ªä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°çš„æ­£æ•´æ•°ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>è¯æ˜</strong> å‡è®¾ \(n\) æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªæ­£æ•´æ•°ï¼Œä»¤ \(x = (n+1)!+2\)ã€‚å¦‚æœ \(x, x+1, x+2, \cdots , x+(n-1)\) éƒ½ä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°çš„è¯ï¼Œå®šç†å°±å¾—è¯äº†ã€‚æ‰€ä»¥ä¸‹é¢å°±æ¥å¹²è¿™äº‹ï¼š</p>

<p>å¦‚æœæŠŠ \(x\) çš„ 2 æå‡ºæ¥ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{align*}
x &amp; = 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 \cdots (n+1) + 2 \\
&amp; = 2 \cdot (1 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 \cdots (n+1) + 1)
\end{align*}\]

<p>å¯è§ \(x\) å¯ä»¥è¢«å†™ä¸ºä¸¤ä¸ªæ›´å°çš„æ­£æ•´æ•°ä¹‹ä¹˜ç§¯ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥ \(x\) ä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ã€‚åŒç†å¯çŸ¥ï¼Œ\(x + i \ (0 \leq i \leq n - 1)\) ä¹Ÿéƒ½ä¸æ˜¯è´¨æ•°ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{align*}
x + i &amp; = 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 \cdots (n+1) + (i+2) \\
&amp; = (i+2) \cdot (1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdots (i+1) \cdot (i+3) \cdots (n+1) + 1)
\end{align*}\]

<p><strong>è¯æ¯•</strong></p>

<h2 id="1-sentential-logic">1 Sentential Logic</h2>

<h3 id="11-deductive-reasoning-and-logical-connectives">1.1 Deductive Reasoning and Logical Connectives</h3>

<p><strong>Example 1.1.1</strong> ä¸‹é¢æ˜¯ä¸€äº›æ¼”ç»æ¨ç†çš„ä¾‹å­ï¼Œç”¨ä»¥è¯´æ˜ä»€ä¹ˆæ˜¯â€œå‰æâ€ï¼Œâ€œç»“è®ºâ€ï¼Œä»¥åŠä¸€ä¸ªè®ºè¯æ˜¯å¦â€œæœ‰æ•ˆâ€ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>æ˜å¤©è¦ä¹ˆä¸‹é›¨è¦ä¹ˆä¸‹é›ªã€‚<br />
æ˜å¤©å¤ªæš–äº†ä¸ä¼šä¸‹é›ªã€‚<br />
å› æ­¤ï¼Œæ˜å¤©ä¼šä¸‹é›¨ã€‚</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>è¦ä¹ˆç”·ç®¡å®¶æœ‰ç½ªï¼Œè¦ä¹ˆå¥³ä»†æœ‰ç½ªã€‚<br />
è¦ä¹ˆå¥³ä»†æœ‰ç½ªï¼Œè¦ä¹ˆå¨å­æœ‰ç½ªã€‚<br />
å› æ­¤ï¼Œè¦ä¹ˆç”·ç®¡å®¶æœ‰ç½ªï¼Œè¦ä¹ˆå¨å­æœ‰ç½ªã€‚</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>åœ¨æ¯ä¸ªä¾‹å­ä¸­ï¼Œå‰ä¸¤å¥è¯éƒ½æ˜¯ <mark>å‰æï¼ˆpremisesï¼‰</mark>ï¼Œæœ€åä¸€å¥è¯æ˜¯ <mark>ç»“è®ºï¼ˆconclusionï¼‰</mark>ã€‚åªæœ‰å½“å‰æå…¨ä¸ºçœŸèƒ½â€œè¿«ä½¿â€ç»“è®ºä¹Ÿå¿…ä¸ºçœŸæ—¶ï¼Œè¿™ä¸ªè®ºè¯æ‰æ˜¯ <mark>æœ‰æ•ˆï¼ˆvalidï¼‰</mark> çš„ã€‚å› æ­¤ï¼Œç¬¬ä¸€ä¸ªè®ºè¯æ˜¯æœ‰æ•ˆçš„ï¼Œè€Œç¬¬äºŒä¸ªè®ºè¯æ˜¯æ— æ•ˆçš„ã€‚æ³¨æ„ï¼Œæ— è®ºå‰ææˆ–ç»“è®ºåœ¨äº‹å®ä¸Šæ˜¯çœŸæ˜¯å‡ï¼Œéƒ½ä¸å½±å“è®ºè¯çš„æœ‰æ•ˆæ€§ã€‚å³ï¼Œè®ºè¯çš„æœ‰æ•ˆæ€§åªå–å†³äºè®ºè¯çš„å½¢å¼ï¼Œä¸è®ºè¯çš„å†…å®¹æ— å…³ã€‚å¯å°†ç¬¬ä¸€ä¸ªè®ºè¯æŠ½è±¡æˆä»¥ä¸‹å½¢å¼ï¼š</p>

<p>P or Q. <br />
not Q. <br />
Therefore, P.</p>

<p>é‡Œé¢çš„ä¸€äº›è¿è¯ï¼Œé€šå¸¸ç”¨ä»¥ä¸‹ç¬¦å·æ¥è¡¨ç¤ºï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{cc}
Symbol &amp; Meaning \\
\hline
\lor &amp; \text{or (disjunction)} \\
\land &amp; \text{and (conjunction)} \\
\lnot &amp; \text{not (negation)} \\
\end{array}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.1.2</strong> ç”¨ä¸Šè¡¨çš„è¿è¯ç¬¦å·æ¥è¡¨ç¤ºä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘å½¢å¼ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>è¦ä¹ˆ John å»è¶Ÿå•†åº—ï¼Œè¦ä¹ˆæˆ‘ä»¬å°±æ²¡é¸¡è›‹äº†ã€‚</li>
  <li>Joe æ‰“ç®—ç¦»å¼€å®¶ä¸”å†ä¹Ÿä¸å›æ¥ã€‚</li>
  <li>è¦ä¹ˆ Bill åœ¨å¹²æ´»è€Œ Jane é—²ç€ï¼Œè¦ä¹ˆ Jane åœ¨å¹²æ´»è€Œ Bill é—²ç€ã€‚</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(P \lor Q\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ P è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ John å»è¶Ÿå•†åº—â€ï¼ŒQ è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œæˆ‘ä»¬æ²¡é¸¡è›‹â€ã€‚</li>
  <li>\(P \land Q\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ P è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ Joe æ‰“ç®—ç¦»å¼€å®¶â€ï¼ŒQ è¡¨ç¤º â€œ Joe å†ä¹Ÿä¸å›æ¥â€ã€‚</li>
  <li>\((B \land \lnot J)\lor(\lnot B \land J)\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ B è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ Bill åœ¨å¹²æ´»â€ï¼ŒJ è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ Jane åœ¨å¹²æ´»â€ã€‚</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Example 1.1.3</strong> åœ¨ä¸Šä¾‹ä¸­ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬å·²ç»å­¦ä¼šå°†è‡ªç„¶è¯­è¨€è¡¨ç¤ºæˆé€»è¾‘ç¬¦å·çš„å½¢å¼äº†ã€‚åè¿‡æ¥ï¼Œè¯·å°†ä¸‹åˆ—ç¬¦å·æ‰€è¡¨ç¤ºçš„é€»è¾‘å½¢å¼ç¿»è¯‘æˆè‡ªç„¶è¯­è¨€ã€‚æ³¨æ„ï¼Œé€»è¾‘ä¸Šçš„â€œä¸æˆ–éâ€ï¼Œä¸è‡ªç„¶è¯­è¨€ä¸­çš„â€œä¸æˆ–éâ€å¹¶ä¸æ€»æ˜¯ä¸€è‡´çš„ã€‚</p>

<ol>
  <li>\((\lnot S \land L)\lor S\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ S è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ John is stupidâ€ï¼ŒL è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ John is lazyâ€ã€‚</li>
  <li>\(\lnot S \land (L \lor S)\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ S å’Œ L çš„æ„ä¹‰åŒä¸Šã€‚</li>
  <li>\(\lnot (S \land L) \lor S\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ S å’Œ L çš„æ„ä¹‰åŒä¸Šã€‚</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>Either John isnâ€™t stupid and he is lazy, or heâ€™s stupid.</li>
  <li>John isnâ€™t stupid, and either heâ€™s lazy or heâ€™s stupid.</li>
  <li>Either John isnâ€™t both stupid and lazy, or John is stupid.</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="12-truth-tables">1.2 Truth Tables</h3>

<p>é€šè¿‡çœŸå€¼è¡¨æˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥çœ‹åˆ°å½“å‰æä¸ºçœŸæ—¶ç»“è®ºæ˜¯å¦ä¸ºçœŸï¼Œå³ä¸€ä¸ªè®ºè¯æ˜¯å¦æœ‰æ•ˆã€‚å¦‚ä¸‹é¢â€œä¸â€ã€â€œæˆ–â€ã€â€œéâ€çš„çœŸå€¼è¡¨ã€‚æ³¨æ„ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬çš„â€œæˆ–â€å…è®¸ P å’Œ Q åŒæ—¶ä¸ºçœŸã€‚</p>

\[\begin{array}{cccc}
P &amp; Q &amp; P \land Q &amp; P \lor Q \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F \\
F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T \\
\end{array}
\quad
\begin{array}{cc}
P &amp; \lnot P \\
\hline
F &amp; T \\
T &amp; F \\
\end{array}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.2.1</strong> ä¸‹é¢æˆ‘ä»¬æ¥å®è·µä¸€ä¸‹ï¼Œä¸º \(\lnot (P \lor \lnot Q)\) å†™å‡ºçœŸå€¼è¡¨ã€‚</p>

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

\[\begin{array}{ccccc}
P &amp; Q &amp; \lnot Q &amp; P \lor \lnot Q &amp; \lnot (P \lor \lnot Q) \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F \\
F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F \\
T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F \\
\end{array}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.2.2</strong> é‡åˆ°æ›´å¤æ‚çš„å¼å­ï¼Œå°±è¯¥ç”¨æ›´ç®€æ´çš„å†™æ³•äº†ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚ï¼š \(\lnot (P \land Q) \lor \lnot R\)</p>

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

<p>éº»çƒ¦çš„å†™æ³•ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
P &amp; Q &amp; R &amp; P \land Q &amp; \lnot(P \land Q) &amp; \lnot R &amp; \lnot(P \land Q)\lor \lnot R \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T \\
F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T \\
F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T \\
T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T \\
T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F \\
\end{array}\]

<p>ç®€æ´çš„å†™æ³•ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{ c c }
\text{Step 1} &amp; \text{Step 2} \\
\begin{array}{ c c c }
P &amp; Q &amp; \lnot (P \lor \lnot Q) \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; \quad \textbf{F} \quad \quad \textbf{F} \\
F &amp; T &amp; \quad \textbf{F} \quad \quad \textbf{T} \\
T &amp; F &amp; \quad \textbf{T} \quad \quad \textbf{F} \\
T &amp; T &amp; \quad \textbf{T} \quad \quad \textbf{T} \\
\end{array} &amp;

\begin{array}{ c c c }
P &amp; Q &amp; \lnot (P \lor \lnot Q) \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; \quad F \quad \textbf{T}\ F \\
F &amp; T &amp; \quad F \quad \textbf{F}\ T \\
T &amp; F &amp; \quad T \quad \textbf{T}\ F \\
T &amp; T &amp; \quad T \quad \textbf{F}\ T \\
\end{array} \\

\text{Step 3} &amp; \text{Step 4} \\
\begin{array}{ c c c }
P &amp; Q &amp; \lnot (P \lor \lnot Q) \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; \quad F\ \textbf{T}\ T\ F \\
F &amp; T &amp; \quad F\ \textbf{F}\ F\ T \\
T &amp; F &amp; \quad T\ \textbf{T}\ T\ F \\
T &amp; T &amp; \quad T\ \textbf{T}\ F\ T \\
\end{array} &amp;

\begin{array}{ c c c }
P &amp; Q &amp; \lnot (P \lor \lnot Q) \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; \textbf{F}\ F\ T\ T\ F \\
F &amp; T &amp; \textbf{T}\ F\ F\ F\ T \\
T &amp; F &amp; \textbf{F}\ T\ T\ T\ F \\
T &amp; T &amp; \textbf{F}\ T\ T\ F\ T \\
\end{array} \\

\end{array}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.2.3</strong> å‰é¢ä¸€ç›´åœ¨è¯´ç”¨çœŸå€¼è¡¨å¯ä»¥åˆ¤æ–­ä¸€ä¸ªè®ºè¯æ˜¯å¦æœ‰æ•ˆï¼Œç°åœ¨æ¥çœ‹ä¸‹æ€ä¹ˆåšã€‚è¯·åˆ¤æ–­ä»¥ä¸‹è®ºè¯æ˜¯å¦æœ‰æ•ˆï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Either John isnâ€™t stupid and he is lazy, or heâ€™s stupid. <br />
John is stupid. <br />
Therefore, John isnâ€™t lazy.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The butler and the cook are not both innocent. <br />
Either the butler is lying or the cook is innocent. <br />
Therefore, the butler is either lying or guilty.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>ä»¤ S è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œJohn is stupidâ€ï¼ŒL è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œJohn is lazyâ€ï¼Œåˆ™è®ºè¯çš„çœŸå€¼è¡¨ä¸ºï¼š</li>
</ol>

\[\begin{array}{cc:cc:c}
&amp; &amp; \text{Premises} &amp; &amp; \text{Conclusion} \\
S &amp; L &amp; (\lnot S \land L) \lor S &amp; S &amp; \lnot L \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T \\
F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F \\
T &amp; F &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} \\
T &amp; T &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{F} \\
\end{array}\]

<p>å¯è§ï¼Œå½“å‰æå…¨ä¸ºçœŸæ—¶ï¼Œç»“è®ºæ—¢å¯ä¸ºçœŸä¹Ÿå¯ä¸ºå‡ã€‚æ‰€ä»¥è¿™ä¸ªè®ºè¯æ— æ•ˆã€‚</p>

<ol>
  <li>ä»¤ B è¡¨ç¤ºä¸ºâ€œThe butler is innocentâ€ï¼ŒC è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œThe cook is innocentâ€ï¼ŒL è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œThe butler is lyingâ€ï¼Œåˆ™è®ºè¯çš„çœŸå€¼è¡¨ä¸ºï¼š</li>
</ol>

\[\begin{array}{ccc:cc:c}
&amp; &amp; &amp; \text{Premises} &amp; &amp; \text{Conclusion} \\
B &amp; C &amp; L &amp; \lnot(B \land C) &amp; L \lor C &amp; L \lor \lnot B \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} \\
F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} \\
F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} \\
T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F \\
T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} &amp; \textbf{T} \\
T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F \\
T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T \\
\end{array}\]

<p>å¯è§ï¼Œå½“å‰æå…¨ä¸ºçœŸæ—¶ï¼Œç»“è®ºä¹Ÿå…¨ä¸ºçœŸã€‚æ‰€ä»¥è¿™ä¸ªè®ºè¯æœ‰æ•ˆã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 1.2.4</strong> çœŸå€¼è¡¨ä¸ä»…èƒ½å¤Ÿå¸®åŠ©åˆ¤æ–­ä¸€ä¸ªè®ºè¯æ˜¯å¦æœ‰æ•ˆï¼Œè¿˜èƒ½å¸®åŠ©åˆ¤æ–­ä¸¤ä¸ªå‘½é¢˜æ˜¯å¦ç­‰ä»·ã€‚ä¾‹å¦‚ï¼Œåˆ¤æ–­ä»¥ä¸‹å¼å­æ˜¯å¦ç­‰ä»·ï¼š</p>

\[\lnot(P \land Q), \quad \lnot P \land \lnot Q, \quad \lnot P \lor \lnot Q\]

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

<p>åˆ—å‡ºå„å¼çš„çœŸå€¼è¡¨ï¼Œè‹¥æ— è®ºå‰æå¦‚ä½•ï¼Œç»“è®ºçš„çœŸå€¼éƒ½ç›¸åŒï¼Œåˆ™å¼å­æ˜¯ç­‰ä»·çš„ã€‚</p>

\[\begin{array}{ccccc}
P &amp; Q &amp; \lnot(P \land Q) &amp; \lnot P \land \lnot Q &amp; \lnot P \lor \lnot Q \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T \\
F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F \\
\end{array}\]

<p>å¯è§ï¼Œç¬¬ä¸€ä¸ªå¼å­å’Œç¬¬ä¸‰ä¸ªå¼å­æ˜¯ç­‰ä»·çš„ã€‚äº‹å®ä¸Šï¼Œè¿™è¢«ç§°ä¸º DeMorganâ€™s lawsã€‚é™¤æ­¤ä¹‹å¤–è¿˜æœ‰å¾ˆå¤šå¸¸ç”¨çš„ lawsï¼š</p>

<p><strong>DeMorganâ€™s laws</strong></p>

\[\lnot (P \land Q) \text{ is equivalent to } \lnot P \lor \lnot Q. \\
\lnot (P \lor Q) \text{ is equivalent to } \lnot P \land \lnot Q.\]

<p><strong>Commutative laws</strong></p>

\[P \land Q \text{ is equivalent to } Q \land P. \\
P \lor Q \text{ is equivalent to } Q \lor P.\]

<p><strong>Associative laws</strong></p>

\[P \land (Q \land R) \text{ is equivalent to } (P \land Q) \land R. \\
P \lor (Q \lor R) \text{ is equivalent to } (P \lor Q) \lor R.\]

<p><strong>Idempotent laws</strong></p>

\[P \land P \text{ is equivalent to } P. \\
P \lor P \text{ is equivalent to } P.\]

<p><strong>Distributive laws</strong></p>

\[P \land (Q \lor R) \text{ is equivalent to } (P \land Q) \lor (P \land R). \\
P \lor (Q \land R) \text{ is equivalent to } (P \lor Q) \land (P \lor R).\]

<p><strong>Absorption laws</strong></p>

\[P \lor (P \land Q) \text{ is equivalent to } P. \\
P \land (P \lor Q) \text{ is equivalent to } P.\]

<p><strong>Double Negation law</strong></p>

\[\lnot \lnot P \text{ is equivalent to } P.\]

<p><strong>Example 1.2.5</strong> ä¸Šé¢çš„å„ç§ laws èƒ½å¸®åŠ©æˆ‘ä»¬å°†çœ‹ä¸Šå»å¾ˆå¤æ‚çš„å‘½é¢˜ç®€åŒ–æˆæ›´å®¹æ˜“æ‡‚çš„å½¢å¼ã€‚ä¾‹å¦‚ï¼Œè¯·ç®€åŒ–ä»¥ä¸‹å¼å­ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\lnot(P \lor \lnot Q)\)</li>
  <li>\(\lnot(Q \land \lnot P) \lor P\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

\[\begin{array}{lrll}
1.\ \lnot(P \lor \lnot Q) \\
&amp; \text{is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot P \land \lnot \lnot Q &amp; \text{(DeMorgan's law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot P \land Q &amp; \text{(double negation law).} \\
\\
2.\ \lnot(Q \land \lnot P) \lor P \\
&amp; \text{is equivalent to} &amp; (\lnot Q \lor \lnot \lnot P) \lor P &amp; \text{(DeMorgan's law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; (\lnot Q \lor P) \lor P &amp; \text{(double negation law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot Q \lor (P \lor P) &amp; \text{(associative law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot Q \lor P &amp; \text{(idempotent law),} \\
\end{array}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.2.6</strong> æˆ‘ä»¬æŠŠåƒ \(P \lor \lnot P\) è¿™æ ·æ’ä¸ºçœŸçš„å‘½é¢˜å« <mark>é‡è¨€å¼ï¼ˆtautologyï¼‰</mark>ï¼Œè€Œåƒ \(P \land \lnot P\) è¿™æ ·æ’ä¸ºå‡çš„å‘½é¢˜å« <mark>çŸ›ç›¾å¼ï¼ˆcontradictionï¼‰</mark>ã€‚é‚£ä¹ˆï¼Œä»¥ä¸‹çš„å‘½é¢˜ä¸­ï¼Œå“ªäº›æ˜¯é‡è¨€å¼ï¼Œå“ªäº›æ˜¯çŸ›ç›¾å¼ï¼Ÿ</p>

\[P \lor (Q \lor \lnot P), \quad P \land \lnot(Q \lor \lnot Q), \quad P \lor \lnot(Q \lor \lnot Q)\]

<p><em>Solution</em> é¦–å…ˆå¯¹ä»¥ä¸Šå‘½é¢˜åšå¼ çœŸå€¼è¡¨ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{ccccc}
P &amp; Q &amp; P \lor (Q \lor \lnot P) &amp; P \land \lnot (Q \lor \lnot Q) &amp; P \lor \lnot (Q \lor \lnot Q) \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F \\
F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; F \\
T &amp; F &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; F &amp; T \\
\end{array}\]

<p>å¯è§ï¼Œ\(P \lor (Q \lor \lnot P)\) æ˜¯é‡è¨€å¼ï¼Œ\(P \land \lnot(Q \lor \lnot Q)\) æ˜¯çŸ›ç›¾å¼ã€‚</p>

<p>å†æ¥ä¸€äº›å…³äºé‡è¨€å¼å’ŒçŸ›ç›¾å¼çš„ lawsï¼š</p>

<p><strong>Tautology laws</strong></p>

\[P \land \text{(a tautology) is equivalent to } P. \\
P \lor \text{(a tautology) is a tautology. } \\
\lnot \text{(a tautology) is a contradiction. }\]

<p><strong>Contradiction laws</strong></p>

\[P \land \text{(a contradiction) is a contradiction. } \\
P \lor \text{(a contradiction) is equivalent to } P. \\
\lnot \text{(a contradiction) is a tautology.}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.2.7</strong> ç»ƒä¹ è¿ç”¨ä»¥ä¸Š laws æ¥ç®€åŒ–ä»¥ä¸‹å¼å­ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(P \lor (Q \land \lnot P)\)</li>
  <li>\(\lnot (P \lor (Q \land \lnot R))\land Q\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

\[\begin{array}{lrll}
1.\ P \lor (Q \land \lnot P) \\
&amp; \text{is equivalent to} &amp; (P \lor Q) \land (P \lor \lnot P) &amp; \text{(distributive law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; P \lor Q &amp; \text{(tautology law)} \\
\\
2.\ \lnot (P \lor (Q \land \lnot R)) \land Q \\
&amp; \text{is equivalent to} &amp; (\lnot P \land \lnot (Q \land \lnot R)) \land Q &amp; \text{(DeMorgan's law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; (\lnot P \land (\lnot Q \lor \lnot \lnot R)) \land Q &amp; \text{(DeMorgan's law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; (\lnot P \land(\lnot Q \lor R))\land Q &amp; \text{(double negation law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot P \land ((\lnot Q \lor R) \land Q) &amp; \text{(associative law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot P \land (Q \land (\lnot Q \lor R)) &amp; \text{(commutative law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot P \land ((Q \land \lnot Q) \lor (Q \land R)) &amp; \text{(distributive law),} \\
&amp; \text{which is equivalent to} &amp; \lnot P \land (Q \land R) &amp; \text{(contradiction law).} \\
\end{array}\]

<h3 id="13-variables-and-sets">1.3 Variables and Sets</h3>

<p>å¯¹äºå‘½é¢˜â€œ2 is a prime numberâ€æˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥ç”¨å˜é‡ \(x\) æ¥è¡¨ç¤º 2ï¼Œå› æ­¤å‘½é¢˜å°±å˜æˆâ€œ\(x\) is a prime numberâ€ã€‚æˆ‘ä»¬ç”šè‡³å¯ä»¥ç”¨ä¸€ä¸ªå­—æ¯æ¥ä»£è¡¨æ•´ä¸ªå‘½é¢˜ï¼Œæ¯”å¦‚ \(P(x)\) æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªå…³äº \(x\) çš„å‘½é¢˜ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 1.3.1</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘å½¢å¼ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(x\) is a prime number, and either \(y\) or \(z\) is divisible by \(x\).</li>
  <li>\(x\) is a man and \(y\) is a woman and \(x\) likes \(y\), but \(y\) doesnâ€™t like \(x\).</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(P(x) \land (D(y,x) \lor D(z,x))\)</li>
  <li>\(M(x)\land W(y) \land L(x,y) \land \lnot L(y,x)\)</li>
</ol>

<p>å› ä¸ºä¹‹å‰çš„å‘½é¢˜ä¸å«å˜é‡ï¼Œè¦ä¹ˆä¸ºçœŸè¦ä¹ˆä¸ºå‡ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥éœ€è¦è®¨è®ºçš„æƒ…å†µå¾ˆç®€å•ã€‚ä½†æ˜¯ï¼Œå½“å‘½é¢˜ä¸­å«æœ‰å˜é‡æ—¶ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜çš„çœŸå‡å°±å–å†³äºå˜é‡çš„å–å€¼äº†ã€‚ä¾‹å¦‚ \(P(x)\) è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ\(x\) is a prime numberâ€ï¼Œå½“ \(x=2\) æ—¶ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜ä¸ºçœŸï¼›å½“ \(x=4\) æ—¶ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜å´ä¸ºå‡äº†ã€‚ä¸ºäº†è§£å†³è¿™ä¸ªé—®é¢˜ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬éœ€è¦å¼•å…¥ <mark>çœŸå€¼é›†åˆï¼ˆtruth setï¼‰</mark> çš„æ¦‚å¿µã€‚çœŸå€¼é›†åˆå°±æ˜¯ä»¤â€œ\(P(x)\) ä¸ºçœŸâ€çš„ \(x\) çš„å–å€¼é›†åˆï¼Œå³ï¼š</p>

\[\text{Truth set of } P(x) = \{x \mid P(x)\}.\]

<p>æ¥ä¸‹æ¥ï¼Œå›é¡¾ä¸€ä¸‹é›†åˆè®ºçš„åŸºæœ¬çŸ¥è¯†ã€‚<mark>é›†åˆï¼ˆsetï¼‰</mark> é‡Œçš„ä¸œè¥¿å« <mark>å…ƒç´ ï¼ˆelementï¼‰</mark>ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚ï¼Œé›†åˆ \(\{ 3,7,14 \}\) çš„å…ƒç´ åŒ…æ‹¬ 3ï¼Œ7 å’Œ 14ï¼Œå…ƒç´ çš„é¡ºåºå¯ä»¥ä¸ºä»»æ„ã€‚æ³¨æ„ï¼Œ\(x \neq \{x\}\)ï¼Œå› ä¸ºå‰è€…æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªå…ƒç´ ï¼Œè€Œåè€…æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªé›†åˆã€‚\(7 \in A \) è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ7 æ˜¯æ­¤é›†åˆçš„ä¸€ä¸ªå…ƒç´ â€ï¼Œ\(11 \notin A \) è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œ11 ä¸æ˜¯æ­¤é›†åˆçš„å…ƒç´ â€ã€‚å¦‚æœæ˜¾å¼åœ°è¡¨ç¤ºæ‰€æœ‰è´¨æ•°çš„é›†åˆï¼Œå³â€œB = the set of all \(x\) such that \(x\) is a prime numberâ€ï¼Œåˆ™ä¸ºï¼š</p>

\[B=\{x \mid x \text{ is a prime number }\}\]

<p>å…¶ä¸­ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜â€œ\(x\) is a prime numberâ€æ˜¯é›†åˆçš„ <mark>å…ƒç´ æµ‹è¯•ï¼ˆelementhood testï¼‰</mark>ã€‚è¦æƒ³çŸ¥é“æŸä¸ªä¸œè¥¿æ˜¯å¦ä¸ºé›†åˆä¸­çš„å…ƒç´ ï¼Œåªéœ€è¦çœ‹å®ƒèƒ½ä¸èƒ½ä»¤å…ƒç´ æµ‹è¯•ä¸ºçœŸã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 1.3.2</strong> ç”¨å…ƒç´ æµ‹è¯•çš„å½¢å¼é‡å†™ä»¥ä¸‹é›†åˆï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(E = \{2,4,6,8,\cdots\}\)</li>
  <li>\(P = \{\text{George Washington, John Adams, Thomas Jefferson, James Madison,} \cdots\}\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(E = \{n \mid n \text{ is a positive even integer}\}\)</li>
  <li>\(P = \{z \mid z \text{ was a president of the United States}\}\)</li>
</ol>

<p>åœ¨å‘½é¢˜ \(y \in \{x \mid x^2 &lt; 9\}\) ä¸­ï¼Œ\(y\) æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ª <mark>è‡ªç”±å˜é‡ï¼ˆfree variableï¼‰</mark>ï¼Œè¡¨ç¤ºæ­¤å‘½é¢˜è¯•å›¾è¯´æ˜çš„ä¸œè¥¿ï¼Œæ”¹å˜å®ƒçš„å–å€¼ä¼šæ”¹å˜å‘½é¢˜çš„æ„æ€å¹¶å½±å“å®ƒçš„çœŸå€¼ã€‚è€Œ \(x\) æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ª <mark>çº¦æŸå˜é‡ï¼ˆbound variableï¼‰</mark>ï¼Œä¹Ÿå¯ç§°ä¸º <mark>è™šå˜é‡ï¼ˆdummy variableï¼‰</mark> ï¼Œå®ƒåªä¸è¿‡æ˜¯ä¸ºäº†ä¾¿äºæˆ‘ä»¬è¡¨è¾¾æ„æ€è€Œå¼•å…¥çš„å˜é‡ï¼Œæ”¹å˜å®ƒçš„å˜é‡åå¹¶ä¸å½±å“å‘½é¢˜çš„æ„æ€æˆ–çœŸå€¼ã€‚æˆ‘ä»¬ç§° \(\{x \mid \cdots \}\) <mark>çº¦æŸï¼ˆbindï¼‰</mark> äº†å˜é‡ \(x\)ã€‚</p>

<p>æ³¨æ„ï¼š\(\{x \mid P(x)\}\) åªæ˜¯ä¸ªé›†åˆè€Œä¸æ˜¯å‘½é¢˜ï¼Œ\(y \in \{x \mid P(x)\}\) æ‰æ˜¯ä¸ªå‘½é¢˜ï¼Œä¸”å®ƒä¸ \(P(y)\) æ˜¯åŒä¸€ä¸ªæ„æ€ã€‚éšç€è®²è¿°çš„æ·±å…¥ï¼Œæ¸…æ¥šåœ°åŒºåˆ†â€œä¸œè¥¿çš„è¡¨è¾¾å¼â€å’Œâ€œå‘½é¢˜çš„è¡¨è¾¾å¼â€å°†å˜å¾—è¶Šæ¥è¶Šé‡è¦ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 1.3.3</strong> ä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜æ˜¯ä»€ä¹ˆæ„æ€ï¼Ÿæ¯ä¸ªå‘½é¢˜ä¸­çš„è‡ªç”±å˜é‡æ˜¯å“ªä¸ªï¼Ÿ</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(a + b \notin \{x \mid x \text{ is an even number}\}\)</li>
  <li>\(y \in \{x \mid x \text{ is devisible by } w\}\)</li>
  <li>\(2 \in \{w \mid 6 \notin \{x \mid x \text{ is divisible by } w\}\}\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>æ„æ€ï¼š\(a+b\) ä¸æ˜¯å¶æ•°ã€‚è‡ªç”±å˜é‡ï¼š\(a, b\)</li>
  <li>æ„æ€ï¼š\(y\) èƒ½è¢« \(w\) æ•´é™¤ã€‚è‡ªç”±å˜é‡ï¼š\(y, w\)</li>
  <li>æ„æ€ï¼š2 ä¸èƒ½æ•´é™¤ 6ã€‚æ²¡æœ‰è‡ªç”±å˜é‡ï¼Œä¸”å‘½é¢˜ä¸ºå‡</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Example 1.3.5</strong> è¿˜è®°å¾—ä¹‹å‰çš„â€œçœŸå€¼é›†åˆâ€çš„å®šä¹‰å§ï¼Ÿè¯·è¯´å‡ºä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>Shakespeare wrote \(x\).</li>
  <li>\(n\) is an even prime number.</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\{x \mid \text{Shakespeare wrote } x\} = \{ \text{Hamlet, Macbeth, Twelfth Night,} \cdots\}\)</li>
  <li>\(\{n \mid n \text{ is an even prime number}\}\)</li>
</ol>

<p>å½“å‘½é¢˜åŒ…æ‹¬è‡ªç”±å˜é‡æ—¶ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬é€šå¸¸ä¼šä¸è‡ªè§‰åœ°æ ¹æ®ä¸Šä¸‹æ–‡æ¨æ–­å®ƒæ˜¯ä»€ä¹ˆç±»å‹çš„ä¸œè¥¿ï¼Œæˆ–è€…è¯´æ˜¯å®ƒçš„æ‰€æœ‰å¯èƒ½å–å€¼çš„å…¨é›†ï¼Œå³ï¼Œ<mark>è°ˆè®ºåŸŸï¼ˆuniverse of discourseï¼‰</mark>ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚ï¼š\(\mathbb{R} = \{x \mid x \text{ is a real number}\}\)ã€‚æœ‰æ—¶å€™ï¼Œæ˜¾å¼åœ°å†™å‡ºè°ˆè®ºåŸŸä¼šæ›´å¥½ï¼Œæ¯”å¦‚å°† \(\{x \mid x^2 &lt; 9\}\) å†™ä¸º \(\{x \in \mathbb{R} \mid x^2 &lt; 9\}\)ã€‚å½“è‡ªç”±å˜é‡çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆä¸ºæ•´ä¸ªè°ˆè®ºåŸŸæ—¶ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜æ˜¯é‡è¨€å¼ã€‚ç›¸åçš„ï¼Œå½“è‡ªç”±å˜é‡çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆä¸ºç©ºé›† \(\emptyset\) æ—¶ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜æ˜¯çŸ›ç›¾å¼ã€‚</p>

<h3 id="14-operations-on-sets">1.4 Operations on Sets</h3>

<p>è®¾ \(A\) æ˜¯å‘½é¢˜ \(P(x)\) çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆï¼Œ\(B\) æ˜¯å‘½é¢˜ \(Q(x)\) çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆ \(P(x) \land Q(x),\ P(x) \lor Q(x),\ \lnot P(x)\) çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆæ˜¯ä»€ä¹ˆï¼Ÿ</p>

<p><strong>Definition 1.4.1</strong></p>

<p>The <em>intersection</em> of two sets \(A\) and \(B\) is the set \(A \cap B\) defined as follows:</p>

\[A \cap B =\{x \mid x \in A \text{ and } x \in B\}\]

<p>The <em>union</em> of \(A\) and \(B\) is the set \(A \cup B\) defined as follows:</p>

\[A \cup B =\{x \mid x \in A \text{ or } x \in B\}\]

<p>The <em>difference</em> of \(A\) and \(B\) is the set \(A \setminus B\) defined as follows:</p>

\[A \setminus B =\{x \mid x \in A \text{ and } x \notin B\}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.4.2</strong> è®¾ \(A = \{1,2,3,4,5\},\ B = \{2,4,6,8,10\}\)ï¼Œè¯·åˆ—å‡ºä»¥ä¸‹é›†åˆä¸­çš„å…ƒç´ ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(A \cap B\)</li>
  <li>\(A \cup B\)</li>
  <li>\(A \setminus B\)</li>
  <li>\((A \cup B)\setminus(A \cap B)\)</li>
  <li>\((A \setminus B)\cup(B \setminus A)\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\{2,4\}\)</li>
  <li>\(\{1,2,3,4,5,6,8,10\}\)</li>
  <li>\(\{1,3,5\}\)</li>
  <li>\(\{1,3,5,6,8,10\}\)</li>
  <li>\(\{1,3,5,6,8,10\}\)</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Example 1.4.3</strong> è®¾ \(A = \{x \mid x \text{ is a man}\},\ B = \{x \mid x \text{ has brown hair}\}\)ï¼Œé—®ï¼š\(A \cap B,\ A \cup B,\ A \setminus B\) åˆ†åˆ«æ˜¯ä»€ä¹ˆï¼Ÿ</p>

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

\[A \cap B =\{x \mid x \text{ is a man and } x \text{ has brown hair}\} \\
A \cup B =\{x \mid \text{either } x \text{ is a man or } x \text{ has brown hair}\} \\
A \setminus B =\{x \mid x \text{ is a man and } x \text{ does not have brown hair}\}\]

<p>æˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥åˆ©ç”¨ <mark>éŸ¦æ©å›¾ï¼ˆVenn diagramsï¼‰</mark> æ¥å¸®åŠ©æˆ‘ä»¬ç›´è§‚åœ°ç†è§£æ¶‰åŠä¸‰ä¸ªé›†åˆä»¥ä¸‹çš„é›†åˆè¿ç®—ï¼š</p>

<p><img src="/images/20160603-VennDiagrams-378Ã—245.jpg" /></p>

<p>é›†åˆè®ºä¸­çš„ \(\cap \text{ , } \cup \text{ and } \setminus \) å¯ä»¥åˆ†åˆ«å’Œé€»è¾‘è¿æ¥è¯ \(\land \text{ , } \lor \text{ and } \lnot\) ç›¸å¯¹åº”ã€‚ä½†æ˜¯è¦æ³¨æ„ï¼Œå®ƒä»¬ä¸æ˜¯ç­‰ä»·çš„ï¼šå‰è€…ç”¨äºé›†åˆï¼Œåè€…ç”¨äºå‘½é¢˜ã€‚</p>

\[\text{the truth set of } P(x) \land Q(x) = A \cup B \\
\text{the truth set of } P(x) \lor Q(x) = A \cap B \\
\text{the truth set of } \lnot P(x) = U \setminus A\]

<p><strong>Example 1.4.4</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(x \in A \cap (B \cup C)\)</li>
  <li>\(x \in A \setminus (B \cap C)\)</li>
  <li>\(x \in (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap C)\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(x \in A \land (x \in B \lor x \in C)\)</li>
  <li>\(x \in A \land \lnot (x \in B \land x \in C)\)</li>
  <li>\((x \in A \land x \in B) \lor (x \in A \land x \in C)\)</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Definition 1.4.5</strong> è®¾ A å’Œ B æ˜¯é›†åˆã€‚å¦‚æœ A çš„æ¯ä¸ªå…ƒç´ éƒ½åŒæ—¶æ˜¯ B çš„å…ƒç´ ï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆ A æ˜¯ B çš„ <mark>å­é›†ï¼ˆsubsetï¼‰</mark>ï¼Œè®°ä½œ \(A \subseteq B\)ã€‚å¦‚æœ A å’Œ B æ²¡æœ‰å…±åŒå…ƒç´ ï¼Œå³ \(A \cap B = \emptyset\)ï¼Œåˆ™ç§° A å’Œ B <mark>äº’æ–¥ï¼ˆdisjointï¼‰</mark>ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 1.4.6</strong> è®¾ \(A = {\text{red, green}}, B = {\text{red, yellow, green, purple}} \text{ and } C = {\text{blue, purple}}\)ã€‚å› ä¸º A çš„ä¸¤ä¸ªå…ƒç´  red å’Œ green å‡åœ¨ B ä¸­ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥ \(A \subseteq B\)ã€‚å› ä¸º \(A \cap C = \emptyset\)ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥ A å’Œ C äº’æ–¥ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 1.4.7</strong> å¯¹äºä»»æ„é›†åˆ A å’Œ Bï¼Œ\( (A \cup B) \setminus B \subseteq A\)ã€‚</p>

<h3 id="15-the-conditional-and-biconditional-connectives">1.5 The Conditional and Biconditional Connectives</h3>

<p>æ¥ä¸‹æ¥ä»‹ç»ä¸€ä¸ªæ–°çš„é€»è¾‘è¿æ¥è¯ï¼š\(\to\)ã€‚æˆ‘ä»¬ç”¨ \(P \to Q\) æ¥è¡¨ç¤ºâ€If P then Qâ€ã€‚è¿™ç§å‘½é¢˜ç§°ä¸º <mark>æ¡ä»¶å‘½é¢˜ï¼ˆconditional statementï¼‰</mark>ï¼ŒP ç§°ä¸º <mark>å‰ä»¶ï¼ˆantecedentï¼‰</mark>ï¼ŒQ ç§°ä¸º <mark>åä»¶ï¼ˆconsequentï¼‰</mark>ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 1.5.1</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>If itâ€™s raining and I donâ€™t have my umbrella, then Iâ€™ll get wet.
<!-- 2. If Mary did her homework, then the teacher won't collect it, and if she didn't, then he'll ask her to do it on the board. --></li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\((R \land \lnot U) \to W\)</li>
  <li>\((H \to \lnot C) \land (\lnot H \to B)\)</li>
</ol>

<p>ç”±ä»¥ä¸‹çœŸå€¼è¡¨å¯å¾—ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{cccccc}
P &amp; Q &amp; P \to Q &amp; \lnot P \lor Q &amp; \lnot (P \land \lnot Q) &amp; \lnot Q \to \lnot P\\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T \\
F &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T \\
T &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F &amp; F \\
T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T &amp; T
\end{array}\]

<p><strong>Conditional laws</strong></p>

\[P \to Q = \lnot P \lor Q = \lnot (P \land \lnot Q)\]

<p><strong>Contrapositive law</strong></p>

\[P \to Q \text{ is equivalent to } \lnot Q \to \lnot P\]

<p><strong>Example 1.5.2</strong> ä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜ï¼Œå“ªäº›æ˜¯ç­‰ä»·çš„ï¼Ÿ</p>

<ol>
  <li>If itâ€™s either raining or snowing, then the game has been canceled.</li>
  <li>If the game hasnâ€™t been canceled, then itâ€™s not raining and itâ€™s not snowing.</li>
  <li>If the game has been canceled, then itâ€™s either raining or snowing.</li>
  <li>If itâ€™s raining then the game has been canceled, and if itâ€™s snowing then the game has been canceled.</li>
  <li>If itâ€™s neither raining nor snowing, then the game hasnâ€™t been canceled.</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\((R \lor S) \to C\)</li>
  <li>\(\lnot C \to (\lnot R \land \lnot S)\)ï¼Œå’Œå‘½é¢˜ 1 ç­‰ä»·</li>
  <li>\(C \to (R \lor S)\)</li>
  <li>\((R \to C) \land (S \to C)\)ï¼Œå’Œå‘½é¢˜ 1 ç­‰ä»·</li>
  <li>\(\lnot (R \lor S) \to \lnot C\)</li>
</ol>

<p>åœ¨æ•°å­¦ä¸­ï¼Œ\(P \to Q\) é€šå¸¸è¿˜è¢«è¡¨è¾¾ä¸ºå…¶ä»–å½¢å¼ï¼š</p>

<p>P implies Q.<br />
Q, if P.<br />
P only if Q.<br />
P is a sufficient condition for Q.<br />
Q is a necessary condition for P.</p>

<p><strong>Example 1.5.3</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>If at least ten people are there, then the lecture will be given.</li>
  <li>The lecture will be given only if at least ten people are there.</li>
  <li>The lecture will be given if at least ten people are there.</li>
  <li>Having at least ten people there is a sufficient condition for the lecture being given.</li>
  <li>Having at least ten people there is a necessary condition for the lecture being given.</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(T \to L\)</li>
  <li>\(L \to T\)</li>
  <li>\(T \to L\)</li>
  <li>\(T \to L\)</li>
  <li>\(L \to T\)</li>
</ol>

<p>åœ¨æ•°å­¦ä¸­ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬ç»å¸¸é‡åˆ° \(P \to Q\) å’Œ \(Q \to P\) åŒæ—¶ä¸ºçœŸçš„æƒ…å†µã€‚ä¸ºäº†æ–¹ä¾¿ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬å¼•å…¥ä¸€ä¸ªæ–°çš„è¿æ¥è¯ \(\leftrightarrow\) æ¥è¡¨ç¤º if and only if (iff)ã€‚è€Œåœ¨ç°å®ä¸­ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬è¯´ if æ—¶ï¼Œç»å¸¸å®æŒ‡çš„æ˜¯ if and only ifï¼Œå®ƒç›¸å½“äº \((P \to Q) \land (\lnot P \to \lnot Q)\)ã€‚çœŸå€¼è¡¨å¦‚ä¸‹ï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{ccc}
P &amp; Q &amp; P \leftrightarrow Q \\
\hline
F &amp; F &amp; T \\
F &amp; T &amp; F \\
T &amp; F &amp; F \\
T &amp; T &amp; T
\end{array}\]

<p><strong>Example 1.5.4</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>The game will be canceled iff itâ€™s either raining or snowing.</li>
  <li>Having at least ten people there is a necessary and sufficient condition for the lecture being given.</li>
  <li>If John went to the store then we have some eggs, and if he didnâ€™t then we donâ€™t.</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(C \leftrightarrow (R \lor S)\)</li>
  <li>\(T \leftrightarrow L\)</li>
  <li>\(S \leftrightarrow E\)</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="2-quantificational-logic">2 Quantificational Logic</h2>

<h3 id="21-quantifiers">2.1 Quantifiers</h3>

<p>æˆ‘ä»¬å·²ç»çŸ¥é“ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜ P(x) å«æœ‰ä¸€ä¸ªè‡ªç”±å˜é‡ xï¼Œå½“ x å–æŸäº›å€¼æ—¶å‘½é¢˜ä¸ºçœŸï¼Œè€Œå½“ x å–å¦ä¸€äº›å€¼æ—¶å‘½é¢˜ä¸ºå‡ã€‚æœ‰æ—¶æˆ‘ä»¬ä¼šå…³å¿ƒï¼Œæœ‰å¤šå°‘ä¸ªå–å€¼èƒ½ä»¤ P(x) ä¸ºçœŸã€‚æ›´å…·ä½“åœ°ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬æƒ³è¯´â€œå¯¹äº x æ‰€æœ‰å¯èƒ½çš„å–å€¼ï¼Œå‘½é¢˜ P(x) éƒ½ä¸ºçœŸâ€ï¼Œæˆ–è€…â€œè‡³å°‘å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ª x çš„å–å€¼ï¼Œä»¤å‘½é¢˜ P(x) ä¸ºçœŸâ€ã€‚å› æ­¤ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬å¼•è¿›äº†ä¸¤ä¸ªæ–°çš„ç¬¦å·æ¥å¸®åŠ©æˆ‘ä»¬è¡¨è¾¾è¿™äº›æ„æ€ã€‚å®ƒä»¬ç§°ä¸º <mark>é‡è¯ï¼ˆquantifiersï¼‰</mark>ã€‚</p>

<p>\(\forall x P(x)\) çš„æ„æ€æ˜¯ï¼šå¯¹äºæ‰€æœ‰çš„ xï¼ŒP(x)ã€‚\(\forall\) æ˜¯ <mark>å…¨ç§°é‡è¯ï¼ˆuniversal quantifierï¼‰</mark>ã€‚å³ï¼ŒP(x) çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆä¸º \(U\)ã€‚</p>

<p>\(\exists x P(x)\) çš„æ„æ€æ˜¯ï¼šå­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ª xï¼Œä»¤ P(x)ã€‚\(\exists\) æ˜¯ <mark>å­˜åœ¨é‡è¯ï¼ˆexistential quantifierï¼‰</mark>ã€‚å³ï¼ŒP(x) çš„çœŸå€¼é›†åˆä¸º \(\emptyset\)ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.1.1</strong> ä»¥ä¸‹çš„å¼å­ä»€ä¹ˆæ„æ€ï¼Ÿå®ƒä»¬æ˜¯çœŸæ˜¯å‡ï¼Ÿ</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\forall x(x^2 \ge 0)\)ï¼Œè°ˆè®ºåŸŸä¸º \(\mathbb{R}\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists x(x^2-2x+3=0)\)ï¼Œè°ˆè®ºåŸŸä»ç„¶ä¸º \(\mathbb{R}\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists x(M(x) \land B(x))\)ï¼Œè°ˆè®ºåŸŸä¸ºæ‰€æœ‰äººï¼ŒM(x) æŒ‡ x is a manï¼ŒB(x) æŒ‡ x has brown hair</li>
  <li>\(\forall x(M(x) \to B(x))\)ï¼Œè°ˆè®ºåŸŸå’Œå‘½é¢˜åŒä¸Š</li>
  <li>\(\forall x L(x,y)\)ï¼Œè°ˆè®ºåŸŸä¸ºæ‰€æœ‰äººï¼ŒL(x,y) æŒ‡ x likes y</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>å¯¹äºæ‰€æœ‰çš„å®æ•°ï¼Œ\(x^2 \ge\)ã€‚çœŸ</li>
  <li>å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ªå®æ•°ï¼Œ\(x^2-2x+3=0\)ã€‚å‡</li>
  <li>å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ªæ£•è‰²å¤´å‘çš„ç”·äººã€‚çœŸ</li>
  <li>å¯¹äºæ‰€æœ‰äººï¼Œå¦‚æœä»–æ˜¯ç”·äººï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆä»–ä¸€å®šæ˜¯æ£•è‰²å¤´å‘çš„ã€‚å‡</li>
  <li>æ‰€æœ‰äººéƒ½å–œæ¬¢ yã€‚åªæœ‰å½“ç¡®å®š y æ˜¯è°åï¼Œæ‰èƒ½çŸ¥é“å‘½é¢˜çš„çœŸå‡ã€‚åœ¨æ­¤ï¼Œy å½±å“äº†å‘½é¢˜çš„çœŸå‡ï¼Œæ˜¯è‡ªç”±å˜é‡ï¼›x æ˜¯çº¦æŸå˜é‡</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Example 2.1.2</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>Someone didnâ€™t do the homework</li>
  <li>Everything in that store is either overpriced or poorly made</li>
  <li>Nobodyâ€™s perfect</li>
  <li>Susan likes everyone who dislikes Joe</li>
  <li>\(A \subseteq B\)</li>
  <li>\(A \cap B \subseteq B \setminus C\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\exists x \lnot H(x)\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x [S(x) \to (O(x) \lor P(x))]\)</li>
  <li>\(\lnot \exists x P(x)\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x [\lnot L(x,Joe) \to L(Susan,x)]\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x (x \in A \to x \in B)\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x [(x \in A \land x \in B) \to (x \in B \land x \notin C)]\)</li>
</ol>

<p>åœ¨æè¿°å…³ç³»æ—¶ï¼Œæ˜¾å¼åœ°å†™å‡ºå¦ä¸€æ–¹ä¼šæ›´å¥½ã€‚ä¾‹å¦‚ï¼ŒSome students are married. æˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥ç®€å•åœ°å†™æˆ \(\exists x (S(x) \land M(x))\)ã€‚æ›´å¥½çš„å†™æ³•æ˜¯ \(\exists x (S(x) \land \exists y M(x,y))\)ï¼Œå³ Some students are married <em>to someone</em>.</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.1.3</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>Everybody in the dorm has a roommate he doesnâ€™t like</li>
  <li>Nobody likes a sore loser</li>
  <li>Anyone who has a friend who has the measles will have to be quarantined</li>
  <li>If anyone in the dorm has a friend who has the measles, then everyone in the dorm will have to be quarantined</li>
  <li>If \(A \subseteq B\), then \(A\) and \(C \setminus B\) and disjoint</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Soluitons</strong></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\forall x [D(x) \to \exists y (D(y) \land \lnot L(x,y))]\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x (S(x) \to \lnot \exists y L(y,x))\)ã€‚è¿™é¢˜æœ‰ç‚¹è„‘ç­‹æ€¥è½¬å¼¯ï¼Œå› ä¸º a sore loser å¹¶ä¸æŒ‡ a particular sore loserï¼Œè€Œæ˜¯æŒ‡ all sore loser</li>
  <li>\(\forall x [\exists y (F(x,y) \land M(y)) \to Q(x)]\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists x [D(x) \land \exists y (F(x,y) \land M(y))] \to \forall z (D(z) \to Q(z))\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x (x \in A \to x \in B) \to \lnot \exists x (x \in A \land x \in C \land x \notin B)\)</li>
</ol>

<p>å½“å‡ºç°å¤šä¸ªé‡è¯æ—¶ï¼Œä¸ºäº†ç†æ¸…æ€è·¯ï¼Œæœ€å¥½æ¯æ¬¡ä¸€ä¸ªã€ä¾æ¬¡è€ƒè™‘ã€‚åŒæ—¶è¦æ³¨æ„ï¼Œé‡è¯åœ¨å‘½é¢˜ä¸­çš„å‰åé¡ºåºä¸å¯è½»æ˜“æ”¹å˜ï¼Œå› ä¸ºè¿™å¯èƒ½ä¼šå½±å“å‘½é¢˜çš„æ„æ€å’ŒçœŸå‡ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.1.4</strong> ä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜æ˜¯ä»€ä¹ˆæ„æ€ï¼Ÿå®ƒä»¬æ˜¯çœŸæ˜¯å‡ï¼Ÿæ³¨ï¼šè°ˆè®ºåŸŸå‡ä¸º \(\mathbb{N}\)ï¼Œæ‰€æœ‰è‡ªç„¶æ•°çš„é›†åˆã€‚</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\forall x \exists y (x &lt; y)\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists y \forall x (x &lt; y)\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists x \forall y (x &lt; y)\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall y \exists x (x &lt; y)\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists x \exists y (x &lt; y)\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x \forall y (x &lt; y)\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>å¯¹äºæ¯ä¸€ä¸ªè‡ªç„¶æ•° xï¼Œéƒ½å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ªæ¯”å®ƒå¤§çš„è‡ªç„¶æ•° yã€‚çœŸ</li>
  <li>å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ªè‡ªç„¶æ•° yï¼Œä½¿å¾—æ‰€æœ‰çš„è‡ªç„¶æ•°éƒ½æ¯”å®ƒå°ã€‚å‡</li>
  <li>å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ªè‡ªç„¶æ•° xï¼Œä½¿å¾—æ‰€æœ‰çš„è‡ªç„¶æ•°éƒ½æ¯”å®ƒå¤§ã€‚å‡</li>
  <li>å¯¹äºæ¯ä¸€ä¸ªè‡ªç„¶æ•° yï¼Œéƒ½å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ªæ¯”å®ƒå°çš„è‡ªç„¶æ•° xã€‚å‡</li>
  <li>å­˜åœ¨è‡ªç„¶æ•° x å’Œ yï¼Œä½¿å¾— x &lt; yã€‚çœŸ</li>
  <li>å¯¹äºæ¯ä¸€ä¸ªè‡ªç„¶æ•° xï¼Œå®ƒéƒ½æ¯”æ‰€æœ‰è‡ªç„¶æ•°å°ã€‚å‡</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="22-equivalences-involving-quantifiers">2.2 Equivalences Involving quantifiers</h3>

<p><strong>Quantifier Negation laws</strong></p>

\[\lnot \exists x P(x) = \forall x \lnot P(x) \\
\lnot \forall x P(x) = \exists x \lnot P(x)\]

<p><strong>Example 2.2.1</strong> å¦å®šè¿™äº›å‘½é¢˜ï¼Œå¹¶å°†å…¶é‡æ–°è¡¨ç¤ºæˆè‚¯å®šå¼ã€‚</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(A \subseteq B\)</li>
  <li>Everyone has a relative he doesnâ€™t like</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\lnot A \subseteq B = \lnot \forall x (x \in A \to x \in B) = \exists x (x \in A \land x \notin B)\)</li>
  <li>\(\lnot \forall x \exists y (R(x,y) \land \lnot L(x,y)) = \forall x \forall y (R(x,y) \to L(x,y))\)</li>
</ol>

<p>æ³¨æ„ï¼Œå½“æˆ‘ä»¬è°ˆè®ºä¸¤ä¸ªäº‹ç‰© x å’Œ y æ—¶ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬å¹¶æ²¡æœ‰æ’é™¤ x å’Œ y æ˜¯åŒä¸€ä¸ªä¸œè¥¿çš„å¯èƒ½æ€§ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚ï¼Œâ€œx é‡å©šäº†â€çš„æ­£ç¡®å¼å­æ˜¯ \(\exists y \exists z (M(x,y) \land M(x,z) \land y \neq z)\)ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.2.2</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘å½¢å¼ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>All married couples have fights</li>
  <li>Everyone likes at least two people</li>
  <li>John likes exactly one person</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\forall x \forall y(M(x,y) \to F(x,y))\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x \exists y \exists z (L(x,y) \land L(x,z) \land y \neq z)\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists x [L(John,x) \land \lnot \exists y (L(John,y) \land y \neq x)]\)</li>
</ol>

<p>æœ‰æ—¶å€™ï¼ŒæŠŠè°ˆè®ºåŸŸæ˜¾å¼åœ°å†™å‡ºæ¥ä¼šæ›´æ¸…æ¥šã€‚æ¯”å¦‚æ²¡æœ‰çº¦æŸå˜é‡çš„å½¢å¼ \(\forall x \in \mathbb{R} P(x)\) å’Œæœ‰çº¦æŸå˜é‡çš„å½¢å¼ \(\forall x &gt; 0 \exists y &lt; 0 (y^2 = x)\)ã€‚</p>

<p>æœ‰çº¦æŸå˜é‡çš„å¼å­å…¶å®å¯ä»¥å†™æˆæˆ‘ä»¬ç†Ÿæ‚‰çš„æ— çº¦æŸå˜é‡çš„å½¢å¼ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚ \(\exists x \in A P(x) = \exists x (x \in A \land P(x))\)ã€‚</p>

<p>ä¹‹å‰ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬éƒ½æ˜¯ä¾é çœŸå€¼è¡¨æ¥åˆ¤æ–­å‘½é¢˜çš„çœŸå‡ã€‚è€Œè¿™ä¸€æ‹›æ— æ³•ç”¨åœ¨å«æœ‰é‡è¯çš„å‘½é¢˜ä¸Šã€‚æ€ä¹ˆåŠå‘¢ï¼Ÿç¬¬ä¸‰ç« å†ä»‹ç»ã€‚ç°åœ¨æˆ‘ä»¬åªéœ€è¦è®°ä½ï¼š<mark>æ‰€æœ‰çš„æ•°å­¦å‘½é¢˜ç»“æ„éƒ½å¯ä»¥ç”¨æˆ‘ä»¬å·²çŸ¥çš„è¿™äº›ç¬¦å·æ¥è¡¨ç¤º</mark>ï¼ˆ\(\land, \lor, \lnot, \to, \leftrightarrow, \forall, \exists\)ï¼‰ã€‚è¿™æ˜¯å¾ˆç¥å¥‡å¾ˆé‡è¦çš„ä¸€ç‚¹ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.2.3</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>è°ˆè®ºåŸŸä¸ºè‡ªç„¶æ•°é›† \(\mathbb{N}\) <br />
(a) x is a perfect square <br />
(b) x is a multiple of y <br />
(c) x is prime <br />
(d) x is the smallest number that is a multiple of both y and z</li>
  <li>è°ˆè®ºåŸŸä¸ºå®æ•°é›† \(\mathbb{R}\) <br />
(a) The identity element for addition is 0 <br />
(b) Every real number has an additive inverse <br />
(c) Negative numbers donâ€™t have square roots <br />
(d) Every positive number has exactly two square roots</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<p>1(a) \(\exists y (x = y^2)\) <br />
1(b) \(\exists z (x = yz)\) <br />
1(c) \(x &gt; 1 \land \lnot \exists y \exists z (x = yz \land y &lt; x \land z &lt; x)\) <br />
1(d) \(\exists a (x = ya) \land \exists b (x = zb) \land \lnot \exists w (w &lt; x \land \exists c (w = yc) \land \exists d (w = zd))\)</p>

<p>2(a) \(\forall x (x + 0 = x)\) <br />
2(b) \(\forall x \exists y (x + y = 0)\) <br />
2(c) \(\forall x (x &lt; 0 \to \lnot \exists y (y^2 = x))\) <br />
2(d) \(\forall x (x &gt; 0 \to \exists y \exists z (y^2 = x \land z^2 = x \land y \neq z \land \lnot \exists w (w^2 = x \land w \neq y \land w \neq z)))\)</p>

<h3 id="23-more-operations-on-sets">2.3 More Operations on Sets</h3>

<p>å½¢å¦‚ \(P = \{ p_{i} \mid i \in I \}\) çš„é›†åˆå¯ç§°ä¸º <mark>å·²ç´¢å¼•æ—ï¼ˆindexed familyï¼‰</mark>ï¼Œè€Œ I ç§°ä¸º <mark>ç´¢å¼•é›†ï¼ˆindex setï¼‰</mark>ã€‚å…¶ä¸­ï¼Œi å¯ä»¥æ˜¯åŒ…æ‹¬æ•°å­—çš„ä»»ä½•ä¸œè¥¿ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.3.1</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ï¼Œå†™å‡ºæ‰€ä½¿ç”¨çš„é›†åˆè®ºæ¦‚å¿µçš„å®šä¹‰ã€‚</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(y \in \{ \sqrt[3]{x} \mid x \in \mathbb{Q} \}\)</li>
  <li>\( \{ x_{i} \mid i \in I \} \subseteq A\)</li>
  <li>\( \{ n^2 \mid n \in \mathbb{N} \} \text{ and } \{ n^3 \mid n \in \mathbb{N} \} \text{ are not disjoint } \)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\exists x \in \mathbb{Q} (y = \sqrt[3]{x})\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall i \in I (x_{i} \in A)\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists n \in \mathbb{N} \exists m \in \mathbb{N} (n^2 = m^3)\)</li>
</ol>

<p>ç”±äºä»»ä½•ä¸œè¥¿éƒ½å¯ä»¥æˆä¸ºé›†åˆä¸­çš„å…ƒç´ ï¼Œä¸€ä¸ªæœ‰è¶£è€Œæœ‰ç”¨çš„æƒ³æ³•æ˜¯ï¼šå°†ä¸€ä¸ªé›†åˆä½œä¸ºå¦ä¸€ä¸ªé›†åˆçš„å…ƒç´ ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚ \(\mathcal{F} = \{ A, B, C \}\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ \(A = \{ 1, 2, 3 \}, B = \{ 4 \}, C = \emptyset\)ã€‚å› æ­¤ï¼Œ\(1 \in A, A \in \mathcal{F}, 1 \notin \mathcal{F}\)ã€‚</p>

<p>ä¸ºäº†æ–¹ä¾¿ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬ç»å¸¸ä¼šå°†ä¸€æ—é›†åˆå®šä¹‰ä¸ºå·²ç´¢å¼•æ—ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚ \(\mathcal{F} = \{ C_{s} \mid s \in S \}\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­ s æ˜¯æŸä¸ªå­¦ç”Ÿï¼Œ\(C_{s}\) æ˜¯è¯¥ç”Ÿçš„æ‰€æœ‰è¯¾ç¨‹ã€‚ä¸€ç§é‡è¦çš„é›†åˆæ—æ˜¯å¹‚é›†ï¼š</p>

<p><strong>Definition 2.3.2</strong> è®¾ A æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªé›†åˆï¼Œåˆ™ A çš„ <mark>å¹‚é›†ï¼ˆpower setï¼‰</mark> æ˜¯ A çš„æ‰€æœ‰å­é›†çš„é›†åˆï¼Œè®°ä½œ</p>

\[\mathcal{P}(A) = \{x \mid x \subseteq A\}\]

<p><strong>Example 2.3.3</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘ç»“æ„ã€‚</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(x \in \mathcal{P}(A)\)</li>
  <li>\(\mathcal{P}(A) \subseteq \mathcal{P}(B)\)</li>
  <li>\(B \in \{ \mathcal{P}(A) \mid a \in \mathcal{F} \}\)</li>
  <li>\(x \in \mathcal{P}(A \cap B)\)</li>
  <li>\(x \in \mathcal(A) \cap \mathcal(B)\)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\forall y (y \in x \to y \in A)\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall x [\forall y (y \in x \to y \in A) \to \forall y (y \in x \to y \in B)]\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists A \in \mathcal{F}\forall x (x \in B \leftrightarrow \forall y (y \in x \to y \in A))\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall y (y \in x \to (y \in A \land y \in B))\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall y (y \in x \to y \in A) \land \forall y (y \in x \to y \in B)\)</li>
</ol>

<p>åœ¨åˆ†æä¸€ä¸ªå¤æ‚çš„å‘½é¢˜æ—¶ï¼Œä¸€ä¸ªå¾ˆå¥½ç”¨çš„åŸåˆ™æ˜¯ï¼šä»æœ€å¤–é¢çš„ç¬¦å·å¼€å§‹ã€‚</p>

<p>æˆ‘ä»¬ç”¨ \(\cap \mathcal{F}\) æ¥è¡¨ç¤ºè¿™äº›é›†åˆå…±æœ‰çš„å…ƒç´ ï¼Œç”¨ \(\cup \mathcal{F}\) æ¥è¡¨ç¤ºè¿™äº›é›†åˆçš„å…ƒç´ çš„æ€»ä½“ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.3.4</strong> ä»¤ \( \mathcal{F} = \{ \{ 1,2,3,4\}, \{2,3,4,5\}, \{3,4,5,6\} \}\)ï¼Œå†™å‡º \(\cap \mathcal{F}, \cup \mathcal{F}\)ã€‚</p>

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

\[\cap \mathcal{F} = \{3,4\} \\
\cup \mathcal{F} = \{1,2,3,4,5,6\}\]

<p><strong>Definition 2.3.5</strong> è®¾ \(\mathcal{F}\) æ˜¯ä¸€æ—é›†åˆï¼Œåˆ™å®ƒçš„äº¤é›†å’Œå¹¶é›†åˆ†åˆ«ä¸ºï¼š</p>

\[\cap \mathcal{F} = \{x \mid \forall A \in \mathcal{F}(x \in A)\} = \{x \mid \forall A (A \in \mathcal{F} \to x \in A)\} (\mathcal{F} \neq \emptyset)\\
\cup \mathcal{F} = \{x \mid \exists a \in \mathcal{F}(x \in A)\} = \{x \mid \exists A (A \in \mathcal{F} \land x \in A)\}\]

<p><strong>Example 2.3.6</strong> åˆ†æä»¥ä¸‹å‘½é¢˜çš„é€»è¾‘å½¢å¼ã€‚</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(x \in \cap \mathcal{F}\)</li>
  <li>\(\cap \mathcal{F} \nsubseteq \cup \mathcal{G}\)</li>
  <li>\(x \in \mathcal{P}(\cup \mathcal{F})\)</li>
  <li>\(x \in \cup \{ \mathcal{P}(A) \mid A \in \mathcal{F} \} \)</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Solutions</em></p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\forall A (A \in \mathcal{F} \to x \in A)\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists x [\forall A \in \mathcal{F}(x \in A) \land \forall A \in \mathcal{G}(x \notin A)]\)</li>
  <li>\(\forall A (y \in x \to \exists A \in \mathcal{F}(y \in A))\)</li>
  <li>\(\exists A \in \mathcal{F} \forall y (y \in x \to y \in A)\)</li>
</ol>

<p>å°†å¤æ‚çš„æ•°å­¦å‘½é¢˜å†™ä¸ºç”¨é€»è¾‘ç¬¦å·è¡¨è¾¾çš„å½¢å¼ï¼Œèƒ½å¤Ÿå¸®åŠ©æˆ‘ä»¬æ›´å¥½åœ°åˆ¤æ–­å‘½é¢˜çš„çœŸå‡ï¼Œæ¯”å¦‚å½“åŸå½¢å¼æ¯”é€»è¾‘å½¢å¼éœ€è¦æ›´å¤šæ“ä½œæ—¶ã€‚</p>

<p>å¯¹äºå·²ç´¢å¼•æ—é›†åˆï¼Œè¿˜å¯ä»¥ç”¨å¦ä¸€ç§æ–¹å¼æ¥è¡¨ç¤ºï¼šè®¾ \(\mathcal{F} = \{ A_{i} \mid i \in I \}\)ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­æ¯ä¸ª \(A_{i}\) æ˜¯ä¸€ä¸ªé›†åˆï¼Œåˆ™ \(\cap \mathcal{F}\) æŒ‡æ‰€æœ‰ \(A_{i}\) å…±æœ‰çš„å…ƒç´ ï¼Œ\(\cap \mathcal{F} = \cap_{i \in I}A_{i} = \{ x \mid \forall i \in I (x \in A_{i})\}\)ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 2.3.7</strong> è®¾ \(I = \{1,2,3\}\)ï¼Œå¯¹äºæ¯ä¸€ä¸ª \(i \in I\)ï¼Œä»¤ \(A_{i} = \{i, i+1, i+2, i+3\}\)ã€‚æ‰¾å‡º \(\cap_{i \in I}A_{i}, \cup_{i \in I}A_{i}\)ã€‚</p>

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

\[\cap_{i \in I} A_{i} = A_{1} \cap A_{2} \cap A_{3} = \{1,2,3,4\} \cap \{2,3,4,5\} \cap \{3,4,5,6\} = \{3,4\}
\cup_{i \in I} A_{i} = \{1,2,3,4\} \cup \{2,3,4,5\} \cup \{3,4,5,6\} = \{1,2,3,4,5,6\}\]

<p><strong>Example 2.3.8</strong> ç”¨ \(L(x,y)\) è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œx likes yâ€ï¼Œç”¨ \(A(x,y)\) è¡¨ç¤ºâ€œx admires yâ€ã€‚åˆ™å¯¹äºæ¯ä¸€ä¸ªå­¦ç”Ÿ s ï¼Œ\(L_{s}\) æ˜¯ s å–œæ¬¢çš„æ‰€æœ‰å­¦ç”Ÿçš„é›†åˆï¼Œ\(A_{s}\) æ˜¯ s æ¬£èµçš„æ‰€æœ‰å­¦ç”Ÿçš„é›†åˆã€‚è¯·æè¿°ä»¥ä¸‹é›†åˆï¼š</p>

<ol>
  <li>\(\cap_{s \in S}L_{s}\)</li>
  <li>\(\cup_{s \in S}L_{s}\)</li>
  <li>\(\cup_{s \in S}L_{s} \setminus \cup_{s \in S}A_{s}\)</li>
  <li>\(\cup_{s \in S}(L_{s} \setminus A_{s})\)</li>
  <li>\((\cap_{s \in S}L_{s})\cap(\cap_{s \in S}A_{s})\)</li>
  <li>\(\cap_{s \in S}(L_{s} \cap A_{s})\)</li>
  <li>\(\cup_{b \in B}L_{b} \text{, where } B = \cap_{s \in S}A_{s}\)</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="3-proofs">3 Proofs</h2>

<h3 id="31-proof-strategies">3.1 Proof Strategies</h3>

<p>åšè¯æ˜å°±åƒç©æ‹¼å›¾ï¼Œä½ æƒ³æ€ä¹ˆæ‹¼å°±æ€ä¹ˆæ‹¼ï¼Œæ²¡æœ‰ä»»ä½•è§„åˆ™ã€‚å½“ç„¶ï¼Œåœ¨å®é™…æ“ä½œæ—¶ï¼Œä½ ä¸ä¼šæ¯æ‹¼ä¸€å—å°±ç•™ç©ºä¸€å—ã€ç­‰åˆ°æœ€ååœ¨æ¥æŠŠæ´å¡«æ»¡ï¼Œä¹Ÿä¸ä¼šä»ä¸Šåˆ°ä¸‹ã€ä»å·¦åˆ°å³åœ°ä¸¥æ ¼æŒ‰é¡ºåºæ‹¼ã€‚æ›´å¯èƒ½çš„æ˜¯ï¼Œä½ å…ˆæŠŠå››æ¡è¾¹æ‹¼å¥½ï¼Œç„¶åæŠŠä¸€äº›å®¹æ˜“å®Œæˆçš„åŒºåŸŸæ‹¼æˆå¤§å—å„¿ï¼Œå†æŠŠå¤§å—å„¿æ•´åˆèµ·æ¥ã€‚æœ‰æ—¶å€™ä½ ä¼šå‘ç°æŸäº›åœ°æ–¹å¯¹ä¸ä¸Šï¼Œè¯´æ˜ä½ çŠ¯äº†é”™è¯¯ï¼Œéœ€è¦é€€å›é‡æ¥ã€‚åªæœ‰å½“æ‹¼å›¾æœ€åå®Œæˆæ—¶å¯¹æ•´ä¸ªå¤§å±€æœ‰äº†è®¤è¯†ï¼Œä½ æ‰çŸ¥é“ï¼ŒåŸæ¥é‚£æ¡è“çº¿æ˜¯æ¹–è¾¹è€Œä¸æ˜¯å¤©é™…ã€‚</p>

<p>æ•°å­¦å®¶ä»¬é€šå¸¸ç”¨ <mark>å®šç†ï¼ˆtheoremï¼‰</mark> çš„å½¢å¼æ¥è¡¨ç¤ºä¸€ä¸ªæ•°å­¦é—®é¢˜çš„ç­”æ¡ˆï¼šå¦‚æœè¿™ä¸ªå®šç†çš„ <mark>å‡è®¾ï¼ˆhypothesesï¼‰</mark> æ˜¯çœŸçš„ï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆæŸäº›ç»“è®ºä¸€å®šæ˜¯çœŸçš„ã€‚é€šå¸¸ï¼Œè¿™äº›å‡è®¾å’Œç»“è®ºä¸­åŒ…å«ç€è‡ªç”±å˜é‡ï¼Œå®ƒä»¬å¯ä»¥ä¸ºè°ˆè®ºåŸŸä¸­çš„ä»»ä½•å…ƒç´ ã€‚å˜é‡çš„ä¸€ä¸ªå–å€¼ç§°ä¸º <mark>å®ä¾‹ï¼ˆinstanceï¼‰</mark>ã€‚åªæœ‰å¯¹äºå®šç†çš„æ¯ä¸€ä¸ªå®ä¾‹æ¥è¯´ï¼Œå½“å‡è®¾ä¸ºçœŸå…¶ç»“è®ºä¹Ÿä¸ºçœŸæ—¶ï¼Œå®šç†æ‰ä¸ºçœŸã€‚å“ªæ€•ä»…å­˜åœ¨ä¸€ä¸ªå®ä¾‹ï¼Œä»¤å‡è®¾ä¸ºçœŸæ—¶ç»“è®ºå´ä¸ºå‡ï¼Œè¿™ä¸ªå®šç†ä¹Ÿæ˜¯å‡çš„ã€‚è¿™ç§å®ä¾‹ç§°ä¸º <mark>åä¾‹ï¼ˆcounterexampleï¼‰</mark>ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 3.1.1</strong> è€ƒè™‘ä»¥ä¸‹å®šç†ã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Theorem</strong> å¦‚æœ \(x &gt; 3\) ä¸” \(y &lt; 2\)ï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆ \(x^2 - 2y &gt; 5\)ã€‚</p>

<p>æˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥æ‰¾åˆ°ä¸€ä¸ªå®ä¾‹ï¼šx = 5 ä¸” y = 1ã€‚å¯è§å¯¹äºè¿™ä¸ªå®ä¾‹æ¥è¯´ï¼Œå‡è®¾ x &gt; 3 å’Œ y &lt; 2 æ˜¯çœŸçš„ï¼Œç»“è®º \(x^2 - 2y &gt; 5\) ä¹Ÿæ˜¯çœŸçš„ã€‚åœ¨è¿™é‡Œæˆ‘ä»¬æ²¡æœ‰è¯æ˜è¿™ä¸ªå®šç†æ˜¯æ­£ç¡®çš„ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬åªæ£€æŸ¥äº†ä¸€ä¸ªå®ä¾‹ï¼Œè€Œè¯æ˜å®šç†æ­£ç¡®éœ€è¦æ£€æŸ¥æ‰€æœ‰çš„å®ä¾‹ã€‚</p>

<p>äº‹å®ä¸Šï¼Œè¿™ä¸ªå®šç†æ˜¯æ­£ç¡®çš„ã€‚å¦‚æœæˆ‘ä»¬æŠŠç¬¬äºŒä¸ªå‡è®¾å»æ‰ï¼Œåˆ™å¾—åˆ°ä¸€ä¸ªä¸æ­£ç¡®çš„å®šç†ï¼š</p>

<p><strong>Incorrect Theorem</strong> å¦‚æœ \(x &gt; 3\)ï¼Œé‚£ä¹ˆ \(x^2 - 2y &gt; 5\)ã€‚</p>

<p>æˆ‘ä»¬åªéœ€è¦æ‰¾åˆ°ä¸€ä¸ªåä¾‹ï¼Œä¾¿å¯ä»¥åˆ¤æ–­å®šç†ä¸æ­£ç¡®ã€‚æ¯”å¦‚å½“ x = 4 ä¸” y = 6 æ—¶ã€‚</p>

<p>ç”±æ­¤å¯è§ï¼Œæ‰¾åˆ°ä¸€ä¸ªåä¾‹ä¾¿å¯ä»¥ç¡®å®šå®šç†ä¸æ­£ç¡®ï¼Œä½†ç¡®å®šå®šç†æ­£ç¡®çš„å”¯ä¸€æ–¹æ³•æ˜¯è¯æ˜å®ƒã€‚è¯æ˜çš„ç¬¬ä¸€æ¡ç­–ç•¥æ˜¯ï¼š</p>

<p><strong>è‹¥è¦è¯æ˜ä¸€ä¸ªå½¢å¦‚ \(P \to Q\) çš„ç»“è®ºï¼Œ</strong> <br />
å…ˆå‡è®¾ P ä¸ºçœŸï¼Œç„¶åè¯æ˜ Q ä¸ºçœŸã€‚</p>

<p>ç”±äºè¯æ˜ä¸€ä¸ªå‘½é¢˜é€šå¸¸éœ€è¦å¤šæ¬¡è½¬æ¢ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬æŠŠåœ¨æŸä¸€æ—¶åˆ»å·²çŸ¥ä¸ºçœŸæˆ–è¢«å‡è®¾ä¸ºçœŸçš„å‘½é¢˜ç§°ä¸º <mark>å‡å®šï¼ˆgivenï¼‰</mark>ï¼ŒæŠŠå¾…è¯æ˜çš„å‘½é¢˜ç§°ä¸º <mark>ç›®æ ‡ï¼ˆgoalï¼‰</mark>ã€‚äºæ˜¯æˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥å…ˆåˆ©ç”¨å‡å®šå®Œæˆç›®æ ‡çš„è¯æ˜ï¼Œç„¶åå†å›å¤´è¯æ˜å‡å®šä¸ºçœŸã€‚</p>

<p><strong>Example 3.1.2</strong> è®¾ a å’Œ b æ˜¯å®æ•°ï¼Œè¯æ˜ï¼šå¦‚æœ \(0 &lt; a &lt; b\)ï¼Œåˆ™ \(a^2 &lt; b^2\)ã€‚</p>

<p><em>Scratch work</em></p>

\[\begin{array}{cc}
Givens &amp; Goal \\
a \text{ and } b \text{ are real numbers} &amp; (0 &lt; a &lt; b) \to (a^2 &lt; b^2)
\end{array}\]

<p>æ ¹æ®ä¸Šè¿°è¯æ˜æŠ€å·§ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»¬å¯ä»¥å°† 0 &lt; a &lt; b ä½œä¸ºå‡å®šï¼š</p>

\[\begin{array}{cc}
Givens &amp; Goal \\
a \text{ and } b \text{ are real numbers} &amp; a^2 &lt; b^2 \\
0 &lt; a &lt; b &amp;
\end{array}\]

<p>å¯æ¨å¾— \(a^2 &lt; ab, ab &lt; b^2, a^2 &lt; ab &lt; b^2\)ã€‚å› æ­¤ \(a^2 &lt; b^2\)ã€‚</p>

<p><em>Solution</em></p>

<p><strong>Theorem</strong> Suppose a and b are real numbers. If 0 &lt; a &lt; b then a<sup>2</sup> &lt; b<sup>2</sup>.</p>

<p><em>Proof</em> Suppose 0 &lt; a &lt; b. Multiplying the inequality a &lt; b by the positive number a we can conclude that a<sup>2</sup> &lt; ab &lt; b<sup>2</sup>, so a<sup>2</sup> &lt; b<sup>2</sup>, as required. Thus, if 0 &lt; a &lt; b then a<sup>2</sup> &lt; b<sup>2</sup>.</p>

<p>ç”±æ­¤å¯è§ï¼Œæƒ³å‡ºè¯æ˜æ–¹æ³•çš„æ€è€ƒè¿‡ç¨‹å’Œè¯æ˜è¿‡ç¨‹æ˜¯åˆ†å¼€çš„ã€‚å‰è€…æ˜¯å¿ƒç†ï¼Œåè€…æ˜¯æ•°å­¦ã€‚æ‰€ä»¥ä¸€å¼€å§‹çœ‹ä¸æ‡‚è¯æ˜æ˜¯æ­£å¸¸çš„ã€‚ä¸‹é¢æˆ‘ä»¬æŠŠåˆšæ‰ç»™å‡ºçš„è¯æ˜ç­–ç•¥é‡æ–°å‘ˆç°ä¸€éï¼š</p>

<p><strong>To prove a goal of the form \(P \to Q\):</strong><br />
Assume P is true and then prove Q.</p>

<p><em>Scratch work</em></p>

